<module status="bronze">
    <h>à</h>
    <p><g>à</g>
        <en>out of, off, from</en> is the (non-leniting) elative <a
            href="?xx=prepositions/prepositions">preposition</a>.</p>
    <!--<p>The elative preposition <g>à</g> should not be confused with other uses of the particle <a
            href="?gd=a"><g>a</g></a>.</p>-->
    <section>
        <h>forms</h>
        <section id="indefinite">
            <h>indefinite</h>
            <p>The default form of the elative preposition is simply <g>à</g> – <ul>
                    <li><m>à</m> taigh <en>out of a house</en></li>
                    <li><m>à</m> aislingean <en>out of dreams</en></li>
                    <li><m>à</m> Nirribhidh <en>out of Norway</en></li>
                    <!--<li><m>à</m> trì làithean <en>out of three days</en></li>-->
                </ul></p>
            <p>Note that this preposition is often spelled with an acute accent, as in <g>á</g>, in
                older writings, and sometimes even without any accent, as <g>a</g>. It is always
                pronounced as a short, clear [a], and never as long [a:] or as schwa [ə].</p>
        </section>
        <section id="definite">
            <h>definite</h>
            <p>When the immediately following word is a form of the definite article, the linking
                form <g>às</g> is used – <ul>
                    <li><m>às an</m> taigh <en>out of the house</en></li>
                    <li><m>às a’</m> bhaile <en>out of the town</en></li>
                    <li><m>às na h-</m>aislingean <en>out of the dreams</en></li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p><g>às</g> is used in a range of other contexts as well – <ul>
                    <li><g>às na tha ...</g>
                        <en>from what is ...</en></li>
                    <li><g>às gach ...</g>
                        <en>from every ...</en></li>
                    <li><g>às a h-uile ...</g>
                        <en>from every ...</en></li>
                    <li><g>às a bheil ...</g>
                        <en>out of which ... is</en></li>
                    <!--<li><g>às àite</g> 
                        <en>out of place</en></li>-->
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>There are no fused forms with <g>à</g> and a <!--<a
                href="?xx=nouns/possessive_determiners">possessive determiner</a>-->
                possessive determiner – <ul>
                    <li><m>às mo</m> thaigh <en>out of my house</en></li>
                    <li><m>às do</m> bhaile <en>out of your town</en></li>
                    <li><m>às a h-</m>òran <en>out of her song</en></li>
                    <li><m>às a</m> chraoibh <en>out of his tree</en></li>
                    <li><m>às ar n-</m>achadh <en>out of our field</en></li>
                    <li><m>às ur</m> leapannan <en>out of your beds</en></li>
                    <li><m>às an</m> taighean <en>out of their houses</en></li>
                    <li><m>às am</m> baile <en>out of their town</en></li>
                </ul>
            </p>
        </section>
        <section id="pronouns">
            <h>prepositional pronouns</h>
            <p>Conjugated prepositions are used in place of <bad>à mi</bad>, <bad>à thu</bad>, ... ,
                    <bad>à iad</bad> – <ul>
                    <li><m>asam</m>
                        <en>out of me</en></li>
                    <li><m>asad</m>
                        <en>out of you</en></li>
                    <li><m>aiste</m>
                        <en>out of her/it</en></li>
                    <li><m>às</m>
                        <en>out of him/it</en></li>
                    <li><m>asainn</m>
                        <en>out of us</en></li>
                    <li><m>asaibh</m>
                        <en>out of you</en></li>
                    <li><m>asta</m>
                        <en>out of them</en></li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>There are also emphatic forms (cf. <bad>à mise</bad>, <bad>à thusa</bad>, ... ,
                    <bad>à iadsan</bad>) – <ul>
                    <li><m>asamsa</m>
                        <en>out of <emph>me</emph></en></li>
                    <li><m>asadsa</m>
                        <en>out of <emph>you</emph></en></li>
                    <li><m>aistese</m>
                        <en>out of <emph>her/it</emph></en></li>
                    <li><m>às-san</m>
                        <en>out of <emph>him/it</emph></en></li>
                    <li><m>asainne</m>
                        <en>out of <emph>us</emph></en></li>
                    <li><m>asaibhse</m>
                        <en>out of <emph>you</emph></en></li>
                    <li><m>astasan</m>
                        <en>out of <emph>them</emph></en></li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>Finally, there are also reflexive forms (cf. <bad>à mi fhìn</bad>, <bad>à thu
                    fhèin</bad>, ... , <bad>à iad fhèin</bad>) – <ul>
                    <li><m>asam fhèin / fhìn</m>
                        <en>out of myself</en></li>
                    <li><m>asad fhèin</m>
                        <en>out of yourself</en></li>
                    <li><m>aiste fhèin</m>
                        <en>out of herself/itself</en></li>
                    <li><m>às fhèin</m>
                        <en>out of himself/itself</en></li>
                    <li><m>asainn fhèin / fhìn</m>
                        <en>out of ourselves</en></li>
                    <li><m>asaibh fhèin</m>
                        <en>out of yourself</en></li>
                    <li><m>asta fhèin</m>
                        <en>out of themselves</en></li>
                </ul>
            </p>
        </section>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h>dependents</h>
        <section id="comp">
            <h>complements</h>
            <p>Some examples – <ul>
                    <li>pedagogical examples – <xl id="comps-pedag">
                            <li>
                                <gd>Cò às a tha thu? Tha à Glaschu.</gd>
                                <tr>Where are you from? From Glasgow.</tr>
                                <ref text="601">td. 2</ref>
                            </li>
                        </xl>
                    </li>
                    <li>older pedagogical examples – <xl id="comp-older-pedag">
                            <li>
                                <gd>Bha an latha brèagha blàth is thug an athair leis Iain agus Anna
                                    anns a’ chàr. Chaidh iad sìos taobh an locha is stad iad aig
                                    àite bòidheach gorm. Chuir iad an càr a stigh gu taobh an
                                    rathaid is thug iad brat a mach <m>as a’ chàr</m> air son suidhe
                                    air. [...]</gd>
                                <tr>The day was lovely and warm and their father took John and Ann
                                    in the car. They went down the side of the lake and they stopped
                                    at a beautiful green place. They put the car into the side of
                                    the road and they took a blanket out of the car for sitting on.
                                    [...]</tr>
                                <ref text="621">td. 6</ref>
                                <note><a href="?gd=càr">càr</a>
                                    <masc/>
                                    <en>car</en></note>
                            </li>
                        </xl>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>Some idioms – <ul>
                   <!-- <li><g>às <a href="?gd=an-seo">an·seo</a></g>
                        <en>hence</en></li>-->
                   <!-- <li><g>às <a href="?gd=an-sin">an·sin</a></g>, <g>às an àite sin</g>
                        <en>thence</en></li>-->
                    <li><g>à seo</g>, <g>às a seo</g>
                        <en>hence, from here</en></li>
                    <li><g>à sin</g>, <g>às a sin</g>, <g>às an àite sin</g>
                        <en>thence, from there</en></li>
                    <li><g>à fasan</g> / <g>às an fhasan</g>
                        <en>out-of-date, out of fashion</en></li>
                    <li><g>às an t-sreath</g>
                        <en>exceptional</en></li>
                    <li><g>às a’ chumantas</g>
                        <en>out of the usual, abnormal</en></li>
                    <li><g>às an rathad</g>
                        <en>esoteric</en></li>
                    <li><g>à measg ...</g>
                        <en>from among ...</en> – <ul>
                            <li>pedagogical examples – <xl id="a_measg-pedag">
                                    <li>
                                        <gd>Thàinig iad a-mach <m>à measg nan craobh</m>.</gd>
                                        <tr>They came out from among the trees.</tr>
                                        <ref text="601">td. 2</ref>
                                    </li>
                                </xl>
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                </ul>
            </p>
        </section>
    </section>

    <section>
        <h>uses</h>
        <section id="pred">
            <h>predicate</h>
            <module status="bronze" id="bi_a">
                <h>bi à ...</h>
                <p><g><a href="?gd=bi">bi</a> à ...</g>
                    <en>be from ...</en></p>
                <p>Some examples – <ul id="bi-exs">
                        <li>pedagogical examples – <xl id="bi_a-pedag">
                                <li>
                                    <gd>Cò às a tha thu? Tha à Glaschu.</gd>
                                    <tr>Where are you from? From Glasgow.</tr>
                                    <ref text="601">td. 2</ref>
                                </li>
                            </xl>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </module>
        </section>
        <section id="uses-comp">
            <h>complement</h>
            <module id="thig" status="bronze">
                <h>thig à ...</h>
                <p><g><a href="?gd=thig">thig</a> à ...</g>
                    <en>come from somewhere</en></p>
                <p>Some examples – <ul id="thig-exs">
                        <li>pedagogical examples – <xl id="thig-pedag">
                                <li>
                                    <gd>Tha Màiri a’ tighinn a-nall <m>à Glaschu</m>.</gd>
                                    <tr>Mary is coming over here from Glasgow.</tr>
                                    <ref text="609">td. 31</ref>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <gd>Bha e a’ tighinn a-mach às an taigh. Chaidh e a-steach don
                                        togalach às an robh an t-seinn a’ tighinn.</gd>
                                    <tr>He was coming out of the house. He entered the building from
                                        which the singing was coming.</tr>
                                    <ref text="601">td. 49</ref>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <gd>Thuit e anns a’ chadal às nach tig dùsgadh.</gd>
                                    <tr>He fell into the sleep from which comes no awakening.</tr>
                                    <ref text="601">td. 49</ref>
                                </li>
                            </xl>
                        </li>
                        <li>biblical examples – <xl id="thig-bible">
                                <li>
                                    <gd>A Nis is iad so ainmeanna chloinn Israeil, a thàinig do’n
                                        Eiphit; thàinig gach duine agus a theaghlach maille re
                                        Iacob: Reuben, Simeon, Lebhi, agus Iudah, [...] Agus na
                                        h-anman uile <m>a thàinig a mach a leasraidh Iacoib</m>, bu
                                        deich agus tri fichead anam iad; oir bha Ioseph ’san Eiphit
                                        a cheana. [...]</gd>
                                    <tr>Now these are the names of the children of Israel, which
                                        came into Egypt; every man and his household came with
                                        Jacob. Reuben, Simeon, Levi, and Judah, [...] And all the
                                        souls that came out of the loins of Jacob were seventy
                                        souls: for Joseph was in Egypt already. [...] [KJV]</tr>
                                    <ref text="160">Ecsodus I.1–5</ref>
                                </li>
                            </xl>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
                <module id="thig_a_measg" status="bronze">
                    <h>thig à measg ...</h>
                    <p><g>thig à measg ...</g>
                        <en>come from among ...</en></p>
                    <p>Some examples – <ul id="thig_a_measg-exs">
                            <li>pedagogical examples – <xl id="thig_a_measg-pedag">
                                    <li>
                                        <gd>Thàinig iad a-mach à measg nan craobh.</gd>
                                        <tr>They came out from among the trees.</tr>
                                        <ref text="601">td. 2</ref>
                                    </li>
                                </xl>
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>
                </module>
            </module>
